derm","Paraxial mesoderm","Lateral plate mesoderm","Intermediate mesoderm","Surface ectoderm"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eintermediate mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E gives rise to the urogenital system, including the gonads. The gonadal ridge forms from proliferation of intermediate mesoderm and overlying coelomic epithelium around week 5 of development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChordamesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the notochord, which provides structural support and signalling for neural tube development\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParaxial mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms somites, which give rise to skeletal muscle, dermis, and vertebrae\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral plate mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the body wall, limb mesenchyme, and heart\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurface ectoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms epidermis and its derivatives, not internal organs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe shared origin of the urinary and reproductive systems from intermediate mesoderm explains their close anatomical relationship and common developmental abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The gonads develop from intermediate mesoderm during early embryonic development.","The intermediate mesoderm gives rise to both the urinary and reproductive systems, demonstrating their shared developmental origin.","The gonadal ridge forms from proliferation of intermediate mesoderm and coelomic epithelium at week 5."],"references":["Lorenzi V, Vento-Tormo R, Garcia-Alonso L. Human gonadal development, cell by cell. Clin Transl Med. 2022 Dec;12(12):e1123. doi: 10.1002/ctm2.1123. PMID: 36513876; PMCID: PMC9747682.","Xie Y, Wu C, Li Z, Wu Z, Hong L. Early Gonadal Development and Sex Determination in Mammal. Int J Mol Sci. 2022 Jul 6;23(14):7500. doi: 10.3390/ijms23147500. PMID: 35886859; PMCID: PMC9323860.","Gilbert SF. Developmental Biology. 6th edition. Sunderland (MA): Sinauer Associates; 2000. Intermediate Mesoderm. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK10089/","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59645"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16107"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59645"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T21:53:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T21:54:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8798"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74154"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":